Readonly<T>

`Readonly<T>` constructs a type with all properties of `T` set to `readonly`, preventing reassignment.

### Basic Usage

```typescript
interface User {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  email: string;
}

type ReadonlyUser = Readonly<User>;
// { readonly name: string; readonly age: number; readonly email: string }

const user: ReadonlyUser = {
  name: "Alice",
  age: 30,
  email: "alice@example.com"
};

// user.name = "Bob"; // Error: Cannot assign to 'name' because it is a read-only property
```

### How It Works

```typescript
type Readonly<T> = {
  readonly [P in keyof T]: T[P];
};
```

### Shallow vs Deep Readonly

`Readonly<T>` is shallow — nested objects are not readonly:

```typescript
interface Config {
  server: { host: string; port: number };
}

type ReadonlyConfig = Readonly<Config>;

const config: ReadonlyConfig = {
  server: { host: "localhost", port: 3000 }
};

// config.server = { host: "other", port: 80 }; // Error
config.server.host = "other"; // OK - nested not readonly
```

### Deep Readonly

```typescript
type DeepReadonly<T> = {
  readonly [P in keyof T]: T[P] extends object
    ? T[P] extends Function
      ? T[P]
      : DeepReadonly<T[P]>
    : T[P];
};
```

### ReadonlyArray

```typescript
const numbers: readonly number[] = [1, 2, 3];
// numbers.push(4); // Error
// numbers[0] = 10; // Error
console.log(numbers[0]); // OK - reading is fine
```

> **Key Point:** `Readonly` is for compile-time immutability. Use it for configuration objects and DTOs.

codeExample:
// Immutable configuration
interface AppConfig {
  apiUrl: string;
  timeout: number;
  retryAttempts: number;
  features: {
    darkMode: boolean;
    analytics: boolean;
  };
}

const config: Readonly<AppConfig> = {
  apiUrl: "https://api.example.com",
  timeout: 5000,
  retryAttempts: 3,
  features: {
    darkMode: true,
    analytics: false
  }
};

// Function parameter immutability
function processData(data: Readonly<number[]>): number {
  return data.reduce((sum, val) => sum + val, 0);
}

const nums: readonly number[] = [1, 2, 3];
processData(nums);
